    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-04-03T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-04-03T23:00:00-05:00" n="1069"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1069">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">816.00/1233: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in El Salvador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Thurston</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">San Salvador</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-03T22:00:00-06:00"
                            >April 3, 1944—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 4—11:52 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>104. With the other members of the Diplomatic Corps I have just visited President
                    Martínez in the central police barracks. He stated that all organized resistance
                    has ended with the exception of that in the barracks of the second infantry
                    which he expects to overcome within a few hours.</p>
                <p>I felicitated him upon the reestablishment of order.</p>
                <p>The badly led uprising has resulted in moderate loss of life and some property
                    damage the most notable being the destruction by fire of almost an entire block
                    of residence and business buildings in the center of the city.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Thurston</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
